s that have defined their representation in German literature, film, and media. Author Margaret McCarthy investigates female subjectivity as it processes political discourse to define itself through both differences and affinities among women. Ultimately, such a model suggests new ways of re-imagining feminist solidarity across generational, ethnic, and racial lines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aFeminism and literaturezGermany. 0aFeminism and motion pictureszGermany. 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszGermanyxHistoryy21st century. 0aWomen in literature. 0aWomen in motion pictures. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh  aanalysis of trans generational debates.  adifferences and affinities among women.  aethnic and racial lines.  afemale subjectivity.  agerman feminism.  amother daughter themes.  anew cohort of activists.  are imagining feminist solidarity.  arepresentation in german literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311099821440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781785335709?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781785335709423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781785335709/original  a978-3-11-099821-4  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK